ngland":"Monmouth, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Long, Minh, Muoi, Phan, Phat, Vinh, Cuong, Hien, Hoa, Lam, Lan.  Chinese Wing, Chi, Kin, Cheuk, Chi Wai, Chuen, Hon, Keung, Wah, Wai, Chiu, Ho.","Chinese: alternative Mandarin form of the surname 敖, see   Ao  .","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Auerbach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Moshe, Emanuel, Isidor, Bronia, Chaim, Faigy, Menachem, Meyer, Yechezkel.","German: habitational name from any of several places in southern Germany and Austria called Auerbach ‘the stream at the water meadow’. See also 2,   Au  , and   Bach  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from the town of Auerbach in the Upper Palatinate, Bavaria. Compare   Averbach  ."]},{"name":"Ao","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 敖, meaning both ‘rambling’ and ‘deposed king without posthumous titles’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the personal name of <i>Tai Ao</i> (太敖), teacher of the legendary king Zhuanxu (traditional dates: 2514–2437  BC ). (ii) it is said that the surname is also borne by descendants of deposed kings of the former state of Chu, with no posthumous titles, during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC )."]},{"name":"Auer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Hans, Erwin, Matthias, Siegfried, Bernd, Bernhard, Erna, Franz, Fritz, Hermann, Horst.","German (mainly Bavaria): topographic name for someone living by a water meadow, German <i>Au</i>, or a habitational name for someone from a place called Au or Aue (see   Au   and   Aue  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Czechia, and Slovenia."]}]},{"name":"Rhydderch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Roderick  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Roderick","meanings":["Welsh (Glamorgan): Anglicized form of the Welsh personal name <i>Rhydderch</i> (British Celtic <i>Rodercos</i>, presumably meaning ‘great seer’ or ‘most high’), the name of a prominent figure in first-millennium Welsh history. Compare   Prothero  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":3,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Ap Rhydderch was born in 1103, in Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the daughter of Hywel ap Rhys. She had at least 4 sons with Rhydderch Ap Catadog. She died in 1120, in England, at the age of 17."},"et":{"1103–1120":"1103–1120","1062–1132":"1062–1132","1116–Male":"1116–Surnud","1118–Male":"1118–Surnud","1120–1153":"1120–1153","1122–Male":"1122–Surnud","1071–1115":"1071–1115","Aft 1115":"pärast 1115","1132":"1132","1120":"1120","1153":"1153","1062":"1062","1071":"1071","1118":"1118","1106":"1106","1116":"1116","1115":"1115","1103":"1103","about 1118":"umbes 1118","about 1116":"umbes 1116","1122":"1122","Derllys cmt, Carmarthenshire, Wales UK":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","England":"England","of,Monmouth,England":"Monmouth, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1103–1120":"1103–1120","1062–1132":"1062–1132","1116–Male":"1116–Kuollut","1118–Male":"111